===Etymology===
Early 15th century, in sense “sale of offices”, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|baraterie||deceit, trickery}}, from {{m|fro|barat||fraud, deceit, trickery}}, of {{unk.|en}} origin, perhaps {{etyl|cel|en}}.<ref name="oetyld">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> In marine sense of “unlawful acts causing loss to owner”, 1620s.<ref name="oetyld" />

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈbæɹətɹi/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|barratries}}

# the [[act]] of [[persistently]] [[instigate|instigating]] [[lawsuit]]s, often [[groundless]] ones
# the [[sale]] and/or [[purchase]] of [[political]] [[position]]s of [[power]]
# {{label|en|admiralty|_|legal}} [[unlawful]] or [[fraudulent]] acts by the [[crew]] of a [[vessel]], harming the vessel's owner.

